The Master's Hand
nytimes_articles.abstract:
It isn't exactly tantamount to finding a shy unicorn in your garden amid apples of gold, but it will, as the French say, serve. It will do -- and it will do exquisitely, 

     It is most lovable, adorable, electrically surprising -- numinous. And its discovery gives rise to all kinds of contingent hopes and fantasies (the nature of hope being, like that of love, to multiply and expand). Who would have expected it? And yet there it (almost indisputably) is: a langorous marble statue of a young boy, hitherto disregarded, and now acclaimed as an early work  of Michelangelo.

FROM THE DESK OF;In a Single Wire, a New World
nytimes_articles.abstract:
THANKS for taking me home to Shangri-La," wrote A. J., a Nepali student attending West Virginia University. "I'm learning in mountaineer country, or so  they say, but I miss the real mountains." My story of a trek to Rara Lake, in the remote western Himalayas of A. J.'s homeland, had struck a chord. 

     A. J. is a member of a whole new community that I discovered when, at age 40, I left the canyons of Wall Street as a technology consultant to create a business in my Brooklyn brownstone. The venture, started a year ago with my wife, Diane, consists of a couple of tables with metal boxes atop them, connected with a strand of wire that eventually runs out a back window to the world at large, the global village of the Internet's World Wide Web.

nytimes_articles.abstract:
The plastic-wrapped bouquets of red carnations and yellow chrysanthemums descended the closed gates of Abdul Kareem Alsahybi's delicatessen last week like the old ivy on the local brownstones. 

     On the sidewalk outside the hushed Cobble Hill Deli and Grocery at 493 Henry  Street, where Mr. Alsahybi had been shot and killed, people created a shrine, depositing flowers and lighted candles as well as closed cans of beer and open cards of sympathy. Some stood before the candlelight and said Hail Marys for the store owner, who on the night he was murdered was contemplating how to resist the temptations of the store's foods while maintaining his sunrise-to-sunset fast during Ramadan, the Muslim holy month.

nytimes_articles.abstract:
THE sleet was falling and my boots were leaking as I stood outside a drug store on First Avenue, petition in hand. Charles Millard had resigned from his East Side City Council seat on Dec. 1, and anyone who wanted to succeed him had  just 12 days to gather the thousands of signatures needed to qualify for the special election in January. My friend Gifford Miller was game, and his mother, Lynden, and I were out there in the mean sleet with just four days to go. 

     "My son is running for the City Council," Mom said to a well-turned-out young man. "He's a fine fellow. Could you sign this petition so he can get on the ballot?" The preppie's response: "What are you doing bothering people with this  kind of thing in bad weather?" As if we had a choice.

The Tide Is Rising For Refinancing
nytimes_articles.abstract:
THOUGH home sales have not ignited, loan rates are flirting with record lows. 

     In the last few weeks, the average rate on a 30-year mortgage has dipped below the psychologically important barrier of 7 percent several times. At that  level, rates are approaching the 25-year lows recorded in 1993. So not only is it a good time to buy, but it is also a good time for many homeowners to consider refinancing. The potential advantages are several: smaller payments, better cash flow and perhaps more favorable loan terms.

nytimes_articles.headline: Anatomy of a Murder Scene
nytimes_articles.abstract:
STATISTICS NOTWITHSTANDING, THERE IS STILL NO SHORTAGE OF violent crime in New York and, therefore, no shortage of crime scenes. The Crime Scene Unit of the Police Department's detective bureau is the largest of its kind in the country, and the busiest. Based in the Bronx, the unit responded to about 3,000  calls for assistance last year, many of them involving murders; a few C.S.U. detectives were even enlisted to help investigate the Oklahoma City bombing. Some of the unit's 78 detectives and supervisors have also been trained as serologists, entomologists, embalmers, architects and engineers -- the better to determine just how a murder was committed and, consequently, who committed it. 

     As the sirens and spectators recede, C.S.U. detectives stay behind for as long as 14 hours, logging every piece of potential evidence. This is vital work  even in a case where a suspect is identified at the outset, for a conviction (as all of America now knows) will depend on a sound presentation of the evidence. C.S.U. detectives have carried away items as unwieldy as a chunk of Manhattan asphalt, as minuscule as half a strand of hair, as insubstantial as a tiny puddle of body fluids. A "deformed" bullet -- one that has been fired -- is particularly valuable, a fingerprint even more precious. "Eyewitnesses can forget, confessions can be recanted," says Deputy Inspector Phil T. Pulaski, the commanding officer of the forensic investigations division, which includes the C.S.U. "Fingerprints don't lie." It was the print lifted from a can of gasoline  that helped solve the 1993 case in which a Molotov cocktail was thrown into the  cab of a fire truck in Washington Heights, injuring several firemen. In another  case, a fingerprint from a windowpane helped solve the murder of a rabbi's wife  in Brooklyn in 1994.

nytimes_articles.headline: BACKTALK;Cowboys Over America
nytimes_articles.abstract:
What are we to make of the Dallas Cowboys? How is it possible that a football team that was so wildly popular to the cutting-edge mentality of the 1970's is even more popular with a where's-mine mentality of the 1990's? If America's Team has undergone some kind of perverted metamorphosis -- transforming from an iron butterfly of the Landry era to the present Tolkienesque worm that ate Pittsburgh -- or is about to, what are we to make of America? 

     Like the state that gave them birth, the Cowboys have always been not so much an entity as an attitude. In the 70's they were cool, powerful and standoffish.  They used computers to evaluate talent when most people thought of computers as  a new generation of slide rules. The mystique began with the owner Clint Murchison, who set the style by buying his way into the National Football League and then turning all football decisions over to General Manager Tex Schramm and  Coach Tom Landry.

Cheaper by the Dozen: New Cars for Less Than $11,000
nytimes_articles.abstract:
SMALL cars are bigger and better than ever. Many have larger dimensions and a broader choice of options. Even subcompacts have clever designs offering more interior space, or they pack more punch under the hood. And there is a longer list of nameplates from which to choose, from standbys like the Civic and Metro  to newcomers like the Accent and Sephia. 

     Most significantly, all small cars are coming with bigger price tags. To a great extent, this is because Americans have developed such large expectations.  No longer will mainstream buyers tolerate econoboxes that deliver high mileage but shudder in a breeze, or cute bugs with personality galore but faulty heaters.

October was a tough month at our lumber company here. Four employees were injured on the job -- a cut finger, a bruised elbow, that kind of thing. But under our drug-free-workplace policy, all injuries are automatically followed by drug tests, and three of the four tested positive. Because they had been with us less than a year, they were dismissed. 

     Since the dismissals and a campaign to inform all employees about these events, we have had just three injuries, and nobody tested positive.

nytimes_articles.abstract:
FOR the aspiring entrepreneur, the roadblock to owning one's own business is  not lack of foresight, product knowledge, personal drive or planning. The No. 1  impediment is obtaining financing to get the venture started. 

     Many people believe they have the right idea or product to make a go of their own business. Some even have some cash stashed away to back a business, said Stanley Greene, a counselor with the New York State Business Development Center  in White Plains. But most small businesses do not have sufficient funds to adequately finance the venture in the start-up phase. Most of them turn to banks for assistance, only to be turned away for lack of a detailed business plan.

The World;Survival and Suicide in Russia's Shadow
nytimes_articles.abstract:
I N the fall of 1994, shortly before Russia attacked Chechnya to smother its  rebellion, I called on Ahmed Mudarov, in a small village outside of Grozny, the  Chechen capital. Mr. Mudarov had just turned 102, or so said his passport. A Chechen friend who introduced me whispered in my ear: "He's cheating. He's actually 106." 

     Mr. Mudarov, surprisingly erect and lucid, talked about a day in February 1944, when Soviet officers came knocking, Stalin's decree in hand. The entire Chechen nation was to be deported to Central Asia, for collective "collaboration" with Nazi Germany. Five of Mr. Mudarov's children, too sick to travel, were executed on the spot. Calmly, he related how one son, bleeding to death, begged for his help. "I cannot help," replied the father, who was wounded but survived, and was then deported himself. His wife and last surviving child vanished in exile.

VIEWPOINT;Standoff in Cyberspace Gulch
nytimes_articles.abstract:
IN the new frontier that is cyberspace, a showdown is shaping up as the law moves into town. On one side is a band of cybercitizens bent on protecting their privacy as they explore this unmapped territory. On the other are the lawmakers  charged with safeguarding all cybercitizens from crime, even if it means forcing them to give up some of their privacy by, say, signing in as they enter town. 

     This is how the public debate over cyberspace security has been framed. And on-line users are, indeed, worried about security. Yankelovich Partners surveyed 400 randomly selected on-line users, aged 16 and older, by telephone in mid-October and found that 90 percent agree that better Internet security is needed to insure that personal and financial information is not accessible to unauthorized people. Nearly 80 percent believe it is too easy for one's credit card number to be stolen if used on the Internet. And almost 70 percent agree that pornography on the Internet has gone far beyond reasonable bounds.

ECONOMICS -- a relative latecomer to the modern social sciences -- has frequently had occasion to revel in the stature it has achieved. The President has no Council of Sociological Advisers, and there is no Nobel laureate in psychology or history. Economists are everywhere sought after, called upon by governments, corporations and the news media to impart meaning to what so often  seems frightening and confusing -- from our declining wages and stagnating productivity to our endless trade and budget deficits. So why does economics as  a profession seem under siege?

ON THE MAP;Restoring a Castle That Links Paterson's Past and Future
nytimes_articles.abstract:
A piece of Paterson's history is written on the face of Garret Mountain in a  sandstone building known at Lambert's Castle. For those seeking to restore the 103-year-old building, the castle bridges the past and the future, connecting Paterson's glory days as capital of silk manufacturing with the uncertain days to come. 

     In refurbishing the deteriorating mansion, Passaic County officials and historians hope to stir interest in the area's history, especially concerning the story of the silk baron Catholina Lambert, who came to America with five British pounds in his pocket and amassed a fortune. The five-month silk strikes  in 1913 that destroyed the man also contributed to the decline of Paterson as an industrial capital.

TELEVISION REVIEW;Boy Wonder vs. Newspaper King
nytimes_articles.abstract:
Beginning as an imagined life, "Citizen Kane" ended by damaging three real lives. The reputations of William Randolph Hearst and Marion Davies, the movie's undisguised subjects, and the career of Orson Welles, its maker, never recovered. Such is the theme of "The Battle Over Citizen Kane," which combines social history, movie lore a'd psychological interpretation in an engrossing two hours. 

     Tonight's documentary detects a kinship between Hearst, creator of a new kind of journalism and a new kind of empire, and Welles, creator of a new kind of movie. Hearst was in his 70's and Welles was in his 20's when they clashed. They operated in different worlds and their power was of different sorts, but as remembered here by Hearst biographers and Welles collaborators, both were strong-willed, controversy-courting revolutionaries accustomed to getting their  own way.

pages.title: Jacques Chirac
pages.abstract: Jacques Ren Chirac was a French politician who served as President of France from 1995 to 2007. He was previously Prime Minister of France from 1974 to 1976 and 1986 to 1988, as well as Mayor of Paris from 1977 to 1995.

pages.title: Nuclear weapons testing
pages.description: Controlled detonation of nuclear weapons for scientific or political purposes
pages.abstract: Nuclear weapons tests are experiments carried out to determine the performance of nuclear weapons and the effects of their explosion. Over 2,000 nuclear weapons tests have been carried out since 1945. Nuclear testing is a sensitive political issue. Governments have often performed tests to signal strength. Because of their destruction and fallout, testing has seen opposition by civilians as well as governments, with international bans having been agreed on. Thousands of tests have been performed, with most in the second half of the 20th century.
